1. DB Connection Process
 How MongoDB connects locally

When MongoDB is installed locally:

MongoDB server runs on:

mongodb://localhost:27017

Default port → 27017

Example database URL:

mongodb://localhost:27017/mydatabase

 Here:

localhost = your machine

27017 = MongoDB port

mydatabase = database name

What mongoose.connect() does
mongoose.connect("mongodb://localhost:27017/mydatabase")

It:

Connects Node.js to MongoDB

Creates connection pool

Initializes database if not exists

Prepares Mongoose to use schemas & models

Internally:

Opens TCP connection

Authenticates (if required)

Keeps connection alive

 Why we use async/await with try-catch

DB connection takes time (network operation).

So we use async/await:

try {
  await mongoose.connect(DB_URL)
  console.log("DB Connected")
} catch (error) {
  console.log("Connection Failed")
}
Why?

✔ Prevents server crash
✔ Handles connection errors
✔ Makes code readable

 What happens if DB connection fails?

If not handled:
❌ App crashes
❌ Server won’t start
❌ APIs won’t work

With try-catch:
✔ Error logged
✔ You can retry
✔ App can exit safely

2. ORM / ODM Methods Understanding

(Mongoose is actually ODM – Object Document Mapper)

create()
User.create({ name: "Prem" })

 Inserts new document

SQL Equivalent:
INSERT INTO users VALUES (...)
 find()
User.find()

 Gets all documents

SQL Equivalent:
SELECT * FROM users;
 findById()
User.findById("id")

 Gets single document by _id

SQL Equivalent:
SELECT * FROM users WHERE id = ?
 findByIdAndUpdate()
User.findByIdAndUpdate(id, { age: 25 })
SQL Equivalent:
UPDATE users SET age = 25 WHERE id = ?
 findByIdAndDelete()
User.findByIdAndDelete(id)
SQL Equivalent:
DELETE FROM users WHERE id = ?
3. SQL vs MongoDB Mapping
SQL Term	MongoDB Equivalent
Database	Database
Table	Collection
Row	Document
Column	Field
Primary Key	_id
Example:

SQL:

Database → school
Table → students
Row → 1 record

MongoDB:

Database → school
Collection → students
Document → { name: "Prem" }
4. Schema Reading Task

Given:

{
  name: { type: String, required: true },
  role: { type: String, enum: ["admin", "manager"] },
  age: { type: Number, default: 18 }
}
 What validations are applied?
Field	Validation
name	Required
role	Only "admin" or "manager"
age	Default 18
 What happens if role is "user"?

❌ Validation Error

Because:

enum: ["admin", "manager"]

"user" is not allowed.

 What happens if age is not provided?

✔ Automatically set to 18

Because:

default: 18

5.Schema vs Model
 What is Schema?

Schema = Structure / Blueprint

const userSchema = new mongoose.Schema({
  name: String
})

Defines:

Fields

Types

Validations

 What is Model?

Model = Interface to interact with DB

const User = mongoose.model("User", userSchema)

Used to:

create()

find()

update()

delete()

 Why do we need Model after schema?

Schema only defines structure.

Model:
✔ Connects schema to collection
✔ Performs CRUD operations
✔ Creates MongoDB collection

 What happens internally when we run mongoose.model()?

Registers schema

Creates collection (lowercase + plural)

Returns constructor function

Binds model to DB connection
